  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework for unsupervised relation classification that learns structurally grounded confidence through multi-view consistency and dynamic ontology induction. In the absence of labeled data, traditional models produce unreliable confidence scores due to overconfidence on spurious patterns. Our method addresses this by generating multiple complementary views of each sentence—such as dependency-based, semantic-role-based, and context-window-based representations—and encoding them into a shared latent space using specialized encoders. These views are then aligned via a cross-view contrastive objective that encourages consistent relation embeddings when different structural interpretations support the same relational assertion. Confidence is not derived from softmax probabilities but from the degree of agreement across views: high-confidence predictions correspond to cases where all views converge on a similar relation prototype. To avoid reliance on predefined ontologies, we introduce a dynamic clustering mechanism that continuously groups relation embeddings into proto-relations using a meta-clustering algorithm informed by cross-view stability. Clusters with high intra-cluster consistency across views are promoted as canonical relations, while unstable ones are treated as ambiguous or noisy. These stable clusters generate high-quality pseudo-labels used to iteratively refine the encoders via self-training. A gating mechanism modulates the contribution of each view based on its historical reliability, allowing the model to adaptively trust certain views (e.g., syntax) more in domains where they are informative. We further incorporate an uncertainty-aware memory bank that stores relation prototypes with their associated confidence scores, enabling long-term consistency across mini-batches. This creates a bootstrapping process: better confidence leads to better pseudo-labels, which improve the representation learning, which in turn enhances confidence estimation. The final classifier outputs both a predicted relation and a structurally justified confidence score, interpretable via the contributing views. This approach enables applications in low-resource NLP settings such as biomedical text mining or legal document analysis, where labeled data is scarce but structural cues are abundant. By grounding confidence in multi-view consensus rather than isolated model outputs, our method provides a principled solution to the problem of overconfidence in unsupervised settings, offering both higher accuracy and greater interpretability.",
